[{"id":26988,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/nlF6zK1PqE7EQ7DlFgZYNDqzQppqSJdPZNw82EZxKXY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ePAQFeUWjni694d6PRS2Cvi3i9odiEQ7N3UF95hqyEI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/mRJqVMEwM0ChyQaKiw-z6lcmSSDbx01SSHX8VF8iwko.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/hZ06KNyffrSBtes5hnjc64P9bwrNOMErRGbKm6Fl2ZY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26979,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["-CH<sub>3</sub>","-OCH<sub>3</sub>","-COCH<sub>3</sub>","-CH<sub>2</sub>OH"],"answer":2,"solution":"Electron withdrawing group increases the stability of phenoxide&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cnbfdsbfjfbafs.JPG\" style=\"width: 90px; height: 82px;\" /> So <u><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EM0026267_AnsExp_1.jpg\" style=\"width: 102px; height: 66px;\" /></strong></u> would be the best substituent.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (19 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26940,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>573</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Cu</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>300</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>623</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Cu</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>300</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>573</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>300</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>623</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>300</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/16f78586-3935-4aef-a00d-998f79577e99-image.png\" style=\"width: 446px; height: 131px;\" /></p><p>Temperature <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>623</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math></p><p>Pressure <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>300</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26928,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/49963bfd-4331-4a68-b53c-552781c4b4f7-image.png\" style=\"width: 100px; height: 159px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cdfb6695-5b7f-4a7b-b757-dd6a33c95ae8-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 156px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2e9b82c2-bdee-4a7b-88d8-1fa0e256eb24-image.png\" style=\"width: 149px; height: 160px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7191b163-4fba-4e79-9605-7c046f04e218-image.png\" style=\"width: 152px; height: 150px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/40007081-f087-4e74-ba8e-f53dda9bb10c-image.png\" style=\"width: 478px; height: 277px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26816,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"When phenol is treated with dilute $\\text{HNO}_3$ at $298\\text{ K}$, it undergoes electrophilic aromatic substitution to give a mixture of ortho-nitrophenol and para-nitrophenol.<br><br>The mixture is separated by steam distillation. Ortho-nitrophenol is steam volatile due to intramolecular hydrogen bonding, whereas para-nitrophenol is not steam volatile due to intermolecular hydrogen bonding. Thus, the steam volatile compound (X) is ortho-nitrophenol.<br><br>Molecular formula of phenol: $\\text{C}_6\\text{H}_6\\text{O}$<br>Molar mass of phenol $= (6 \\times 12) + (6 \\times 1) + 16 = 94\\text{ g mol}^{-1}$<br>Percentage of oxygen in phenol $= \\dfrac{16}{94} \\times 100 \\approx 17.02\\%$<br><br>Molecular formula of ortho-nitrophenol (X): $\\text{C}_6\\text{H}_5\\text{NO}_3$<br>Molar mass of ortho-nitrophenol $= (6 \\times 12) + (5 \\times 1) + 14 + (3 \\times 16) = 139\\text{ g mol}^{-1}$<br>Percentage of oxygen in ortho-nitrophenol $= \\dfrac{48}{139} \\times 100 \\approx 34.53\\%$<br><br>Increase in percentage of oxygen $= 34.53\\% - 17.02\\% = 17.51\\%$<br><br>We need to express this as $y \\times 10^{-1} \\%$.<br>$17.51\\% = 175.1 \\times 10^{-1} \\%$<br><br>Rounding to the nearest integer, we get $175$.<br><br>Answer: $175$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26823,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Three","Five","Four","Two"],"answer":0,"solution":"A secondary alcohol has the OH group on a carbon bonded to exactly two other carbon atoms. Analyzing each structure:<br><b>I</b> contains only primary alcohols and carboxylic acid.<br><b>II</b> has OH on a carbon bonded to two other carbons (secondary alcohol).<br><b>III</b> has tertiary and primary alcohols only.<br><b>IV</b> has secondary alcohols on the cyclopentanone ring.<br><b>V</b> has OH on a secondary carbon (between two CH groups).<br><b>VI</b> has the central carbon as tertiary with three OH groups.<br>Compounds II, IV, and V contain at least one secondary alcohol, giving total = 3.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26877,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>PhO</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeOH</mi></math>","Benzene, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MeBr</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ph</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>MeO</mi><mo>&#8854;</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>PhO</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></msup><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeBr</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The given methyl phenyl ether can be prepared from&nbsp;Williamson Ether Synthesis.&nbsp;Williamson Ether Synthesis usually takes place as an <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math> reaction of a Alkyl halide with an alkoxide ion. Aryl halides cannot be used in this reaction. The reaction is given below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cabe1b84-ce1a-42a8-8133-d132c3aebf8d.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 83px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26860,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true","Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true but R is NOT the correct explanation of A."],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math> is a measure of  the acidity of a particular molecule. It measures the strength of an acid by how tightly a proton is held by a Bronsted acid. The lower the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math>, the stronger the acid and the greater its ability to donate its protons. describe the acidity of a particular molecule.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>logK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub></math></p><p>Hence, Assertion is true,</p><p>Phenol is more acidic than ethanol because after losing a proton <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mfenced></math>, phenol forms phenoxide ion which is stabilised by resonance whereas ethoxide ion is not.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26848,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c7BiJ3gSK2WAiUOvXdiFAPmSWRNgPaqzAgQju5Uedqw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","\\(\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{OH}\\)","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/O0j_-o5h2qGohYZF5XPKjx-pdGLNi_MK8hhiitxnNFo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/wg3rLJFNKFY8YNzpVDqjQDJXIWMPgGR5Mt6YsgXXFU4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/mTigbHiRCC-VmZx8FrziBspvRpWqGpgdcB-h-3urZXw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26923,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are true"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ddabde21-9e7c-42f8-b2aa-389ca1a8e03a-3c25357c-9c2e-4720-ae92-30afa8e8229d-image.png\" style=\"width: 353px; height: 90px;\" />&nbsp;utilizes <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> moles of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi></math>. One mole for acidic <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> of alkyne and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;moles for&nbsp;ester group.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26837,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{OH}, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}(\\mathrm{Br}) \\mathrm{CH}_3$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCH}_3, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}(\\mathrm{OH}) \\mathrm{CH}_3, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}(\\mathrm{Br}) \\mathrm{CH}_3$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CHO}, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{OH}, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{Br}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CHO}, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}=\\mathrm{CH}_2, \\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}(\\mathrm{Br}) \\mathrm{CH}_3$"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Kd2fTID3HFrs44KIApVbCkSyqiTXhtPTbyRdhtPOP6M.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26862,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/79b5cd08-5431-4f83-9d92-f3f9ce94aea6.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 122px;\"/>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>NaOH</mi><mo> </mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CCl</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>NaOH</mi><mo> </mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HCCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi>NaOH</mi><mo> </mo></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Salicylaldehyde is prepared by heating phenol and chloroform together in the presence of potassium hydroxide or sodium hydroxide. This reaction is called the Reimer-Tiemann reaction.</p><p>The Reimer Tiemann reaction is an organic chemical reaction where phenol is converted into an ortho hydroxy benzaldehyde using chloroform, a base, and an acid workup. This reaction can also be described as the chemical reaction used for the ortho-formylation of phenols.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fbeaa419-2601-4d1e-90e3-57d35126c142.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 146px;\"/></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26973,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6ada4b2e-7663-4653-8e2d-97647ca79ff7-image.png\" style=\"width: 240px; height: 109px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e8984a6a-3243-4633-ab2a-ff8131dbf7e2-image.png\" style=\"width: 240px; height: 106px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/000c8740-e0e7-41f3-b0a4-866536c95c7b-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 96px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e177e688-6f1b-481a-a421-2fcaf9292bc7-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 99px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/240a621d-2fd6-40e8-8f91-96f1c4d2dab3-image.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 322px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (08 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26972,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/yevreorhuwsdqykvbivbyfgfmrtdiljphpusswqlcwcgsrahya.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ivcmudltsyyvkxpfnzrgwnbwfbchtqcwgijtydkxgiluisvuel.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ceahixwyhzvyxpkwdilkeplwrvogeiqmtvykaajsfuofshzndp.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/skrqoidzvztbbfpukwhscbvgujaopadlkodeooomxejevrbmfd.jpeg\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Two different reactions are taking place here Kolbe&ndash;Schmitt reaction and esterification reaction (treatment of the product of Kolbe&ndash;Schmitt reaction with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ester</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;</p><p>The two reactions can be written as follows:</p><p>1.Kolbe&ndash;Schmitt reaction: reaction of phenol with carbon dioxide in the presence of sodium hydroxide, followed by acidification converts phenol to&nbsp;1&minus;1&minus;&nbsp;hydroxybenzoic acid (Salicylic acid).</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>2.Esterification reaction: The salicylic acid is then reacted with acetic anhydride&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo></math>to form aspirin.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img alt=\"solution\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1159994_1033119_ans_afd2281d9c97440b830fea6c7a7e2b91.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 142px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":26870,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p>Ring expansion can go upto seven membered rings</p>","<p>Finally both rings will become six membered each.</p>","<p>Finally both rings will become five membered each.</p>","<p>Only A will become <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math> membered.</p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The reaction proceeds through a carbocation intermediate.&nbsp;The&nbsp;carbocation formed undergo rearrangement by ring expansion. Four membered ring undergo ring expansion to five membered ring and five membered ring undergo ring expansion to six membered ring and finally it converts to alkene by losing proton.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/06f4fe8d-681d-468d-9a3d-8ef8184a2237.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 332px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26929,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c797f8ec-eae4-43b0-82ef-68349e1b8526-image.png\" style=\"width: 202px; height: 112px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7981f870-5d87-416b-8e08-82492fee9ad0-image.png\" style=\"width: 183px; height: 110px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b60442e2-b922-4730-8884-ba9dfc7f3167-image.png\" style=\"width: 222px; height: 116px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d7bc4bee-441e-4680-9290-30fde94d0021-image.png\" style=\"width: 202px; height: 116px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cd071870-f9ad-4129-8563-0fca74e8903e-image.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 377px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26904,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are correct.","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ec7e1d96-f673-476c-a76e-8ec052fbe76d-9754537.png\" style=\"width: 430px; height: 183px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;It is a colorless liquid with a piercing, acrid smell. The smell of burnt fat (as when cooking oil is heated to its smoke point) is caused by glycerol in the burning fat breaking down into acrolein. It does not have fruity smell so, statement II&nbsp;is incorrect.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26913,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a09b4d85-9559-4099-adcf-2af630d560ea-image.png\" style=\"width: 69px; height: 150px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1999421e-9a8e-4a11-afa7-435b9b3fd4f9-image.png\" style=\"width: 151px; height: 130px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1c6629c5-e045-41cf-83df-137d92371d83-image.png\" style=\"width: 141px; height: 100px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7e493045-2ddb-4bbc-8c32-066013854452-9706258_D.png\" style=\"width: 142px; height: 174px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e4a2e435-1f1c-4b50-bb5a-98f3ed2e3e7e-Solution.png\" style=\"width: 435px; height: 347px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26899,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7d5bb4fa-f699-4ac6-adc5-a6e18de30d68-image.png\" style=\"width: 162px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/469f35a9-a6d6-432b-91da-b8e69e8a6047-image.png\" style=\"width: 166px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c2076366-0cf2-4632-8bd0-3ed4e323c770-image.png\" style=\"width: 167px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/99085531-b8d2-4ba5-9d36-f0023aa0ac5f-image.png\" style=\"width: 167px; height: 100px;\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>First step of the reaction involves electrophilic addition of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>in</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math>&nbsp;to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>methyl</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>but</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>ene</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>to&nbsp;form A which contains an ether linkage.</p><p>A, undergoes cleavage reaction with HI&nbsp;by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;mechanism to form B as the major product as shown in the reactions below</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a42af2ac-f2c6-4f08-85ef-139597ec0487-9757174_S.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 257px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26814,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"The chemical reaction of phenol with zinc dust is given by:<br><br>$C_6H_5OH + Zn \\xrightarrow{\\Delta} C_6H_6 + ZnO$<br><br>Product X is benzene ($C_6H_6$).<br><br>Molar mass of phenol ($C_6H_5OH$) = $6 \\times 12 + 6 \\times 1 + 16 = 94$ g mol$^{-1}$<br><br>Number of moles of phenol taken = $\\dfrac{4.7}{94} = 0.05$ mol<br><br>From the stoichiometry of the reaction, 1 mole of phenol produces 1 mole of benzene.<br><br>Theoretical moles of X formed = $0.05$ mol<br><br>Since the reaction goes to $60\\%$ completion, the actual moles of X formed is:<br><br>$0.05 \\times \\dfrac{60}{100} = 0.03$ mol<br><br>This can be written as $3 \\times 10^{-2}$ mol.<br><br>Answer: $3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26815,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; border-collapse: collapse; width: auto;\"><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">D</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">E</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">Conc. H$_2$SO$_4$</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">CH$_2 =$ CH $-$ CH(OH)CH$_3$</td></tr></table>","<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; border-collapse: collapse; width: auto;\"><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">D</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">E</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">PCC</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">HO $-$ CH$_2$ $-$ CH$_2$ $-$ CH $=$ CH$_2$</td></tr></table>","<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; border-collapse: collapse; width: auto;\"><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">D</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">E</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">PCC</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">CH$_2 =$ CH $-$ CH $=$ CH$_2$</td></tr></table>","<table style=\"border: 1px solid black; border-collapse: collapse; width: auto;\"><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">D</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">E</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">Conc. H$_2$SO$_4$ or H$_3$PO$_4$</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">CH$_2 =$ CH $-$ CH $=$ CH$_2$</td></tr></table>"],"answer":3,"solution":"Compound A is pentan-1-ol ($CH_3-CH_2-CH_2-CH_2-CH_2-OH$) and Compound B is pent-1-ene ($CH_2=CH-CH_2-CH_2-CH_3$).<br><br>The conversion of an alcohol to an alkene is a dehydration reaction, which requires an acidic dehydrating agent such as concentrated $H_2SO_4$ or $H_3PO_4$. Thus, reagent D is concentrated $H_2SO_4$ or $H_3PO_4$.<br><br>Compound C is butane-1,3-diol ($HO-CH_2-CH_2-CH(OH)-CH_3$).<br><br>When C is treated with excess dehydrating agent (reagent D), both hydroxyl groups undergo elimination (dehydration). The elimination of two water molecules yields a conjugated diene, which is highly stable due to resonance.<br><br>The product E formed is 1,3-butadiene ($CH_2=CH-CH=CH_2$).<br><br>Answer: <table style=\"border: 1px solid black; border-collapse: collapse; width: auto;\"><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">D</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">E</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">Conc. H$_2$SO$_4$ or H$_3$PO$_4$</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid black; padding: 5px;\">CH$_2 =$ CH $-$ CH $=$ CH$_2$</td></tr></table>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":26849,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_A_IEc75Rex1r9xL6yvWc_4hyhGCd-m7J_s4lT-6GeI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8j7AP9WwVOmxq75tiikT3cplI8ZHNarWxpaH_gGCGCA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Mg2m7JEoOsyo9_PguLarVQLO1td8D9YIbHgvSsWWU4g.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EXMHPqo-HSppoQen4oVJEKGbbHEyJRc4UeVoSWvd1go.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/MX4sW3QFSL4Mmytfy2KNgfMo0_YYLCow6aw3Eri_2MU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26974,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/99f9ae0f-f29b-4a4c-b69b-f7abad57bf33-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 110px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/53bb8aea-873e-45c7-ae8f-a40ffeabb299-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 107px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aa8c7740-d0d6-440f-a2c4-a06be205dc24-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 104px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/50be1e0d-e006-42f9-8474-3d929777783b-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 112px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a9953ec5-697a-4b5e-8df3-f09b6836bf98-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 121px;\" /><br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (08 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27006,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}(\\mathrm{OH}) \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_3$","$\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{OH}$","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Sb5owZQ131ErYaTPLxppQR3eNPQdBSJ1prbIARxBmgA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","$\\mathrm{PhCHOHCH}_3$"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":26880,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/edbccf80-8ad3-423c-a101-0da665bd2a9d-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 105px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ec8fddd7-620e-429b-89c3-0945d2b1698e-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 104px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b4056bc5-46e6-45ed-95e4-1cfa88bd2401-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 107px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9a1f75be-ff78-4aba-b2d9-9e49778233d0-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 185px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The given reaction is an example of dehydration of alcohol. In this reaction the first step is protonation of alcohol which leads to the formation of carbocation. The carbocation formed undergo rearrangement to get stability. The tertiary carbocation formed in this reaction involved in ring closure, which loses proton to from alkene. The steps are shown below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ca2585c9-5d7d-49a0-9f41-3b1b6b88c8c7-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 343px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26967,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["4 - Hydroxypentan - 2-one","3- Hydroxypentan-2-one","1-Pentanol","2-Hydroxycyclopentanone"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">3-Hydroxypentan-2-one and 4-Hydroxypentan-2-one will most readily be dehydrated to give alkene under acidic condition. This will lead to formation of&nbsp;&alpha;&minus;&beta;&nbsp;unsaturated ketone (conjugated system). But out of both 4-Hydroxypentan-2-one will most readily&nbsp;dehydrate to give alkene under acidic condition since the carbocation formed will be more stable than in the case of 3-Hydroxypentan-2-one.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Dehydration of 2-Hydroxycyclopentanone will lead to&nbsp;C=C&nbsp;double bond in 5 member ring that will cause strain and product is less likely to be formed.</p><p><img height=\"108\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/189e91b3-e084-4006-b414-668c02f934f9-image.png\" width=\"173\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (16 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":26953,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e8b46cfe-020b-444a-8177-53ab09670c60-image.png\" style=\"width: 213px; height: 144px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0b66a1ec-ed36-460a-baf2-df040e1b6b84-image.png\" style=\"width: 196px; height: 160px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/af8cb44a-9982-498c-9998-6ca1c89f4fef-image.png\" style=\"width: 212px; height: 163px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/531f7722-6922-42ee-80c7-1c978d813cdb-image.png\" style=\"width: 163px; height: 188px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>-</mo></math>cresol is the m-methyl phenol. Phenol is acidic in nature. It gives the acid-base reaction with base. So, when it reacts with the base, it will form the phenolate ion. After that phenolate ion act as a nucleophile. This nucleophile gives the nucleophilic substitution reaction with the alkyl halide. It will follow the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math> reaction mechanism.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e8e82ac3-804f-4c86-8bd8-ee3130078ff4-image.png\" style=\"width: 781px; height: 199px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27010,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["acetone","acetyl iodide","2- methyl -2-propanol","acetamide"],"answer":2,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":26850,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/guP72ZAMNHFk22iWxRKIeVmKVv5T96HQMCGJsDijS8c.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/hYGS9pxY2LkkzjtcgeMHQTQc-mvoZCbGOU7Cw-iP-CI.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/oFsuCubl-03sMAMX0bhkE4d3DbeWIg0p8Ls1Q_KuzyM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7D3ayxJk_-GX8J-64FWESQk5pUsaqcjzJ_Vph4-fCjc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4qVk7Ez4JRyMrzgS_u3Ke2VSsLVpI-FoVw6M_yTEUXc.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EuURREwdG1h4S5j4VpLIX1JbgmtHUboESWjeJGVFFS0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":26863,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Alcohols Phenols and Ethers","question":"","options":["Salicyclic acid","Benzene-1,2-diol","Benzene-1, 3-diol","2-Hydroxybenzaldehyde"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Chloroform <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi>CHCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced></math> in the presence of an alkali <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>NaOH</mi></mfenced></math> undergoes formylation of phenol at the ortho-position. This is also called as the Reimer-Tiemann reaction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0c717928-6141-4e90-9e6f-77e61cdc75fb.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 164px;\"/>Hence, the answer is option D.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null}]